<h2>Section B: Attempt any EIGHT Questions</h2><h3>Question 4</h3>
<div><p><p>Discuss the strength and weakness of the human visual system. Describe Spline representation for the curve.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>The Strengths of Human Visual:</strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Save money &#8211; If there is an obvious flaw that can be seen by the naked eye, there is no need to take the time and resources to continue the inspection process.</li>
<li>The human element &#8211; Dimensional inspection evaluates just that: <em>the dimensions</em>. But what if the object produced is a mirror image of the intended result? This could be overlooked in an open setup or a non-model-based CMM inspection because the dimensions might exactly match the specifications. However, a visual inspection to compare the final product with the engineering drawings would quickly show the mistake.</li>
<li>Evaluate workmanship -Visually inspecting parts can help ensure that <em>all</em> of the specifications are met, not just the ones the equipment can see.</li>
<li>High-resolution perception: The human eye has a high resolution, allowing us to perceive fine details and distinguish between objects with precision.</li>
<li>Color perception: We have the ability to perceive a wide range of colors, enabling us to appreciate the richness and diversity of the visual world.</li>
<li>Depth perception: Our visual system can perceive depth and three-dimensional space, allowing us to accurately judge distances and perceive the relative positions of objects.</li>
<li>Motion detection: We are highly sensitive to motion, which helps us identify moving objects and track their trajectories.</li>
<li>Pattern recognition: The human brain excels at recognizing and interpreting patterns, allowing us to quickly identify familiar objects and understand complex visual scenes.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>The Weaknesses of Human Visual:</strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Unreliability &#8211; This does not mean that visual inspections are always unreliable, but that they shouldn&#8217;t be your <em>only</em> method of inspection.</li>
<li>Imprecision &#8211; The human eye is not capable of making precise measurements, especially on a very small scale. Even when comparing two similar objects, the eye might not notice that one is slightly smaller or larger than the other. This concept also applies to characteristics such as surface roughness, size, and any other factor that needs to be measured.</li>
<li>Limited field of view: Although our eyes can move and scan the environment, our visual field is limited, and we cannot perceive everything in our surroundings simultaneously.</li>
<li>Sensitivity to light: Our visual system is sensitive to changes in light conditions, and extreme brightness or darkness can impair our vision temporarily.</li>
<li>Optical illusions: Our visual system is susceptible to various optical illusions, where our perception can be easily deceived, leading to incorrect interpretations of visual stimuli.</li>
<li>Inaccurate memory: Human memory is prone to distortions and inaccuracies, and our recollection of visual information can be influenced by external factors or subjective biases.</li>
<li>Blind spots: Each eye has a small region in the retina with no photoreceptor cells, resulting in blind spots where we cannot perceive visual information.</li>
</ul>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-19036" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/spline.jpg?resize=457%2C613&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="457" height="613"></p>
</div>
